        {
          "id": "8.1",
          "title": "Overview of Infection Control",
          "content": "### 8.1 Overview of Infection Control\n\n**Infection control** refers to policies, procedures, and practices used to prevent the spread of infectious agents in healthcare settings. HAIs are largely preventable.\n\n| Term | Definition |\n|---|---|\n| **Infection** | Invasion/multiplication of pathogen in body tissue producing signs/symptoms |\n| **HAI** | Infection acquired during healthcare; not present at admission |\n| **Colonization** | Microorganisms present without causing signs of infection |\n| **Pathogen** | Microorganism capable of causing disease |\n| **Virulence** | Degree of pathogenicity; ability to cause disease |\n\n---"
        },
        {
          "id": "8.2",
          "title": "The Chain of Infection",
          "content": "### 8.2 The Chain of Infection\n\nBreaking **any single link** prevents transmission.\n\n| Link | Definition | Nursing Intervention |\n|---|---|---|\n| **1. Infectious Agent** | The pathogen | Antimicrobials; disinfection; sterilization |\n| **2. Reservoir** | Where pathogen lives/multiplies | Environmental cleaning; waste disposal |\n| **3. Portal of Exit** | How pathogen leaves reservoir | Wound care; respiratory hygiene; sharps disposal |\n| **4. Mode of Transmission** | How it travels to host | Hand hygiene; PPE; isolation |\n| **5. Portal of Entry** | How it enters new host | Sterile technique; catheter care; skin integrity |\n| **6. Susceptible Host** | Person lacking resistance | Immunizations; nutrition; managing chronic illness |\n\n> 💡 **Hand hygiene is the single most effective measure** for breaking the chain of infection.\n\n---"
        },
        {
          "id": "8.3",
          "title": "Modes of Transmission",
          "content": "### 8.3 Modes of Transmission\n\n- **Contact** (most common HAI mode) — direct (person-to-person) or indirect (via contaminated surface/object)\n- **Droplet** — droplets >5 microns; travel ≤3 feet; land on mucous membranes\n- **Airborne** — droplet nuclei ≤5 microns; remain suspended; travel long distances\n- **Vehicle** — contaminated food, water, medications, or IV fluids\n- **Vector-borne** — via animal or insect intermediary\n\n---"
        },
        {
          "id": "8.4",
          "title": "Standard Precautions",
          "content": "### 8.4 Standard Precautions\n\nApplied to **all patients at all times** — treats all blood/body fluids as potentially infectious.\n\n- **Hand hygiene** — before/after every patient contact; after removing gloves; after touching patient environment\n- **PPE** — gloves (blood/body fluid contact); gown (soiling risk); mask + eye protection (splash risk)\n- **Safe sharps handling** — never recap; dispose in puncture-resistant container\n- **Respiratory hygiene/cough etiquette**\n- **Safe injection practices** — never reuse needles or syringes\n\n---"
        },
        {
          "id": "8.5",
          "title": "Transmission-Based Precautions",
          "content": "### 8.5 Transmission-Based Precautions\n\nUsed *in addition to* standard precautions.\n\n| Category | Mode | Common Pathogens | PPE | Room |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Contact** | Direct/indirect contact | MRSA, VRE, *C. diff*, scabies, RSV | Gloves + Gown on entry | Private or cohort |\n| **Droplet** | Droplets >5 microns | Influenza, COVID-19, pertussis, mumps, RSV | Surgical mask within 3 ft | Private preferred |\n| **Airborne** | Droplet nuclei ≤5 microns | TB, measles, varicella | Fit-tested N95 | Negative-pressure room |\n\n**RSV** requires **both contact AND droplet precautions** — gown, gloves, surgical mask within 3 feet, hand hygiene, private room preferred. Negative-pressure room is NOT required.\n\n**Key Notes:**\n- PPE donned *before* entering; doffed *outside* the room\n- *C. difficile* requires soap and water — alcohol-based rubs do **not** kill *C. diff* spores\n\n---"
        },
        {
          "id": "8.6",
          "title": "Aseptic Technique",
          "content": "### 8.6 Aseptic Technique\n\n#### Medical Asepsis (Clean Technique)\n\nReduces and limits microorganisms. Used for routine care not involving penetration of sterile body cavities.\n\n**Core Principles:**\n1. Hand hygiene foundation — wash at least **20 seconds**\n2. Clean to dirty — always move from cleanest to most contaminated\n3. Hold soiled items away from body; discard directly into receptacles\n4. Items are clean, not sterile\n\n**CDC Hand Hygiene Steps:** Wet → soap → lather 20 sec (backs, between fingers, under nails) → rinse → dry → use towel to turn off faucet\n\n#### Surgical Asepsis (Sterile Technique)\n\nComplete elimination of all microorganisms including spores. Required for procedures penetrating skin or entering sterile body cavities.\n\n**Key Principles:**\n- Only sterile items placed within sterile field\n- Sterile objects contaminated when touched by non-sterile objects\n- Sterile fields out of nurse's line of vision = contaminated\n- Wet/damp sterile fields = contaminated (wicking)\n- Outer **1-inch border** of sterile drape = non-sterile\n- Sterile supplies held **above waist level** — below waist = contaminated\n- Pour sterile solutions without touching bottle to field; discard cap once opened\n- Never turn back to or reach across sterile field\n- Open sterile packages **away from the body**\n\n| Feature | Medical Asepsis | Surgical Asepsis |\n|---|---|---|\n| Goal | Reduce microorganisms | Eliminate ALL microorganisms |\n| Equipment | Clean | Sterile |\n| Gloves | Clean | Sterile |\n| Examples | Wound cleaning, oral care, catheter bag emptying | Catheter insertion, IV placement, surgery |\n\n---"
        }
