      "explanation": "**Rationales:**\n\n❌ **Option 1 — Incorrect:** Partial-thickness wound repair applies to injuries that involve only the epidermis and/or the superficial dermis. These wounds heal primarily through epithelial cell migration from the wound edges and remaining hair follicles or sweat glands. Stage I and Stage II pressure ulcers may heal by partial-thickness repair. A Stage IV ulcer, by definition, involves full-thickness tissue loss with exposure of bone, tendon, or muscle — far beyond the superficial layers involved in partial-thickness repair.\n\n✅ **Option 2 — Correct:** A Stage IV pressure ulcer involves full-thickness tissue loss — extending through the dermis, subcutaneous tissue, and exposing deep structures such as bone, tendon, or muscle. These wounds heal by **secondary intention**: the wound fills from the base upward with granulation tissue, then contracts and re-epithelializes. This is a slow process involving significant tissue regeneration, requires meticulous wound management, and results in substantial scar formation. Full-thickness wound repair is the correct framework for planning care.\n\n❌ **Option 3 — Incorrect:** Primary intention healing requires wound edges to be clean, approximated (brought together), and closed — typically with sutures, staples, or surgical adhesive — with minimal tissue loss. This results in a narrow, clean scar. A Stage IV pressure ulcer has extensive tissue loss and an open wound bed that cannot be approximated. Primary intention is the healing method for surgical incisions and clean lacerations, not pressure ulcers. *Note: Primary intention is the correct answer if the question were about wound healing in a post-surgical patient (see Question 43).*\n\n❌ **Option 4 — Incorrect:** Tertiary intention (delayed primary closure) involves intentionally leaving a wound open initially — typically because it is contaminated or infected — and then surgically closing it at a later date once the risk of infection has been controlled. This approach is used for certain traumatic wounds, abscesses, and contaminated surgical sites, not for chronic pressure ulcers. Pressure ulcers are managed as open wounds healing by secondary intention.\n\n---",
