      "correctAnswerText": "1, 2, 3, 6",
      "explanation": "**Rationales:**\n\n✅ **Option 1 — Correct:** When a patient communicates that they are too tired to continue, the nurse must **stop the exercises immediately**. Continuing exercises after a patient has expressed inability or fatigue violates patient autonomy, may cause physical harm (muscle fatigue, injury), and disregards the patient's right to refuse or pause an intervention. The nursing process requires reassessment when a patient's response indicates the current approach is not well-tolerated.\n\n✅ **Option 2 — Correct:** Decreasing the number of repetitions is a clinical adjustment that modifies the intensity of the intervention to match the patient's current tolerance. ROM exercises do not need to be an all-or-nothing proposition — if the patient can complete fewer repetitions safely, that is still clinically valuable and respects patient capacity. This modification should be reflected in the updated care plan.\n\n✅ **Option 3 — Correct:** A patient's fatigue during ROM exercises may indicate that the current plan is too aggressive, that the patient's condition has changed, or that additional assessment is needed. Re-evaluating the care plan — the Evaluation step of ADPIE — is essential. The plan may need to be modified in terms of frequency, duration, intensity, time of day (energy levels vary), or approach (active-assistive vs. passive ROM).\n\n❌ **Option 4 — Incorrect:** Moving to the patient's other side to perform exercises ignores the patient's expressed fatigue. The patient stated she is too tired to go on — she did not say she was tired on only one side. Continuing any ROM exercises after the patient has communicated exhaustion disregards the patient's expressed limits and continues an intervention the patient has declined. This option is a distractor designed to test whether students can distinguish between a meaningful patient report and a nursing workaround.\n\n❌ **Option 5 — Incorrect:** Encouraging the patient to push through fatigue and finish the exercises is a therapeutic boundary violation. It places the nurse's care plan goals above the patient's expressed experience and autonomy. Forcing or coercing a patient to continue an exercise they have stated they cannot tolerate is inappropriate, potentially harmful, and disrespectful of patient-centered care principles. Fatigue during activity in a post-stroke patient may also signal a meaningful clinical change that requires assessment.\n\n✅ **Option 6 — Correct:** Fatigue during mild physical activity such as ROM exercises may indicate more than simple tiredness — it could be a sign of cardiac compromise (reduced cardiac output post-stroke), respiratory impairment, anemia, medication effects, or neurological changes. The nurse must assess the patient for accompanying symptoms — shortness of breath, chest pain, dizziness, pallor, tachycardia — to determine whether the fatigue is expected or clinically significant. Assessment always accompanies any unexpected patient response.\n\n---",
