      "id": 27,
      "title": "Clear Liquid Diet",
      "topic": "Nutrition & Diet Therapy",
      "concept": "Clear Liquid Diet; Allowed and Prohibited Items",
      "unitId": 17,
      "questionText": "A postoperative client is on a clear liquid diet. Which items can the client consume? *(Select all that apply)*",
      "options": [
        {
          "id": "1",
          "text": "Broth"
        },
        {
          "id": "2",
          "text": "Coffee"
        },
        {
          "id": "3",
          "text": "Gelatin"
        },
        {
          "id": "4",
          "text": "Popsicle"
        },
        {
          "id": "5",
          "text": "Ice cream"
        },
        {
          "id": "6",
          "text": "Vegetable juice"
        }
      ],
      "correctIds": [
        "1",
        "2",
        "3",
        "4"
      ],
      "correctAnswerText": "1, 2, 3, 4",
      "explanation": "**Rationales:**\n\n✅ **Option 1 — Correct:** Broth (chicken, beef, or vegetable) is transparent after straining, leaves no residue in the GI tract, and provides minimal calories and electrolytes. It is a foundational clear liquid diet item, particularly valuable for providing some sodium and fluid volume.\n\n✅ **Option 2 — Correct:** Black coffee and plain tea are transparent liquids that are permitted on a clear liquid diet. They do not leave residue and are absorbed without GI stress. *Note: Coffee or tea with cream or milk would NOT be allowed — those add opaque dairy, which is prohibited.*\n\n✅ **Option 3 — Correct:** Gelatin (e.g., Jell-O) is a clear liquid that becomes liquid at body temperature. It is transparent, leaves no residue, and is one of the most commonly ordered clear liquid items. It provides simple carbohydrates and helps advance diet tolerance post-operatively.\n\n✅ **Option 4 — Correct:** Clear popsicles — fruit-flavored, transparent, containing no dairy, cream, or fruit pulp — are permitted on a clear liquid diet. They provide fluid and simple carbohydrates and are often well-tolerated by patients with nausea. *Note: Cream-based or dairy-based popsicles would not be allowed.*\n\n❌ **Option 5 — Incorrect:** Ice cream contains milk, cream, and fat — all opaque, residue-forming dairy components. It is not a clear liquid and is not permitted on a clear liquid diet. Ice cream is appropriate on a **full liquid diet**, which allows all foods that are liquid at room temperature including dairy. *Note: If the question asked about a full liquid diet, ice cream would be a correct answer.*\n\n❌ **Option 6 — Incorrect:** Vegetable juice (e.g., tomato juice, V8) is opaque — it contains suspended vegetable solids and pulp. Even when strained, it does not meet the standard of a clear liquid. Vegetable juice may be appropriate on a soft or regular diet. *Note: Clear fruit juices without pulp — such as apple juice, white grape juice, or cranberry juice — ARE allowed on a clear liquid diet. The key distinction is transparency and absence of pulp.*\n\n---",
