      "id": 34,
      "title": "Types of Exercise: Isotonic",
      "topic": "Activity, Immobility & Patient Positioning",
      "concept": "Types of Exercise; Isotonic vs. Isometric vs. Resistive Isometric",
      "unitId": 18,
      "questionText": "Isotonic, isometric, and resistive isometric are categories of exercise. Which exercises are considered isotonic?",
      "options": [
        {
          "id": "1",
          "text": "Bicycling, swimming, walking, jogging, dancing"
        },
        {
          "id": "2",
          "text": "Tightening or tensing muscles without moving body parts"
        },
        {
          "id": "3",
          "text": "Push-ups, hip lifting, pushing feet against a footboard"
        },
        {
          "id": "4",
          "text": "Quadriceps set exercises and contraction of gluteal muscles"
        }
      ],
      "correctIds": [
        "1"
      ],
      "correctAnswerText": "1",
      "explanation": "**Rationales:**\n\n✅ **Option 1 — Correct:** Isotonic exercises involve **muscle contraction with movement** — the muscle changes in tension, the joint moves through a range of motion, and muscle length changes (shortens or lengthens). These exercises are dynamic and functional. The examples given — bicycling, swimming, walking, jogging, and dancing — all involve rhythmic, repetitive muscle contractions through full ranges of motion. Isotonic exercise is the foundation of cardiovascular conditioning and functional strength rehabilitation.\n\n❌ **Option 2 — Incorrect:** Tightening or tensing muscles without moving body parts describes **isometric exercise**. In isometric contraction, muscle tension increases but the muscle length does not change and no joint movement occurs. Examples include clenching the fist, pressing the palms together, holding a position, and the exercises described in this option. Isometric exercise builds strength without joint movement and is useful when joint motion is contraindicated. *Note: This would be the correct answer if the question asked about isometric exercises.*\n\n❌ **Option 3 — Incorrect:** Push-ups, hip lifts, and pushing the feet against a footboard are examples of **resistive isometric** exercise — the muscle contracts against an external resistance but no joint movement occurs (or minimal movement). These exercises build strength through resistance loading without range of motion. Resistive isometrics are used when joint stability is required or during early rehabilitation when ROM is restricted. *Note: This would be the correct answer if the question asked about resistive isometric exercises.*\n\n❌ **Option 4 — Incorrect:** Quadriceps sets (tightening the quad muscle while the leg is straight) and gluteal contractions (squeezing the buttocks) are **isometric exercises** — no joint movement occurs; only muscle tension changes. These exercises are commonly prescribed post-operatively (e.g., after knee replacement) to maintain muscle tone and prevent atrophy while range of motion is restricted. *Note: These are isometric, same category as option 2.*\n\n---",
