      "explanation": "**Rationales:**\n\n✅ **C — Correct.** Once any portion of a sterile field has been contaminated, the entire field must be considered contaminated — there is no partial contamination in surgical asepsis. The contaminated kit must be discarded and a fresh sterile kit obtained before the procedure can continue. This is non-negotiable and is one of the most fundamental principles of sterile technique.\n\n❌ **A — Incorrect.** Changing to new sterile gloves does not decontaminate the sterile field — it only decontaminates the nurse's hands. If the sterile field itself was touched with non-sterile hands or objects, the supplies on that field remain contaminated regardless of what the nurse does with their gloves afterward. *New sterile gloves are necessary as part of restarting with a new kit, but they do not allow continuation with the contaminated field.*\n\n❌ **B — Incorrect.** Calling for assistance may be necessary in some situations (e.g., if the patient is difficult to position), but it is not the first action when a sterile field is contaminated. The immediate priority is to stop and obtain a new kit. *Calling for assistance might be helpful as a concurrent step, but it does not address the contaminated field.*\n\n❌ **D — Incorrect.** There is no clinical cleaning method that can restore sterility to a contaminated field at the bedside. Wiping a contaminated item with an alcohol swab, for example, achieves disinfection — not sterilization — and is completely inadequate. The field is contaminated; it must be replaced. *This option is impossible to execute correctly — cleansing a sterile field in situ is not a recognized technique.*\n\n---",
