      "explanation": "**Rationales:**\n\n✅ **C — Correct.** Scheduled (prompted) toileting proactively brings the patient to the toilet or bedside commode at regular intervals — before incontinence occurs. This approach preserves dignity by helping the patient maintain continence through planning and routine, rather than reacting to accidents after they happen. It also maintains the patient's active participation in their own elimination care.\n\n❌ **A — Incorrect.** Limiting fluid intake is not only ineffective for preventing incontinence — it is harmful. Concentrated urine irritates the bladder wall, actually worsening urgency and frequency. Adequate fluid intake (approximately 1.5–2 L/day) is necessary for urinary tract health. *Fluid restriction is never an appropriate intervention for incontinence management.*\n\n❌ **B — Incorrect.** Involving family members in intimate personal care tasks such as toileting without the patient's explicit preference and consent is a dignity violation. Many patients are embarrassed by incontinence and would find family involvement mortifying. *Family may assist only if the patient requests and prefers their help.*\n\n❌ **D — Incorrect.** Adult briefs (incontinence pads) address the symptoms of incontinence — containing leakage — but they do not preserve dignity. Many patients find wearing adult briefs demeaning and infantilizing. Briefs may be appropriate as one component of a comprehensive incontinence management plan, but they should not be the only intervention, and they do not constitute the \"best\" approach to preserving dignity. *Briefs are a reactive management tool, not a dignity-preserving strategy.*\n\n---",
