      "explanation": "**Rationales:**\n\n✅ **C — Correct.** An indwelling (Foley) catheter has an inflatable balloon at its distal tip that holds it in place inside the bladder. Before removal, this balloon must be fully deflated by withdrawing all fluid from the inflation port with a syringe. Attempting to remove the catheter with any residual fluid in the balloon forces the intact balloon through the urethra, causing urethral tears, hematuria, severe pain, and potential urethral stricture formation.\n\n❌ **A — Incorrect.** Routine irrigation of the catheter before removal is not indicated and serves no clinical purpose in standard catheter removal. Irrigation would only be appropriate if the catheter were blocked or if a specific clinical order required it. *Pre-removal irrigation is not a standard of care.*\n\n❌ **B — Incorrect.** Clamping the catheter before removal is not a standard practice and serves no beneficial purpose in routine removal. It could increase discomfort if the bladder is filling. *Clamping is used in specific bladder-training protocols before catheter removal in certain patients, but it is not the \"priority action\" for all removals.*\n\n❌ **D — Incorrect.** This option describes the exact error the priority action prevents. Removing a catheter with the balloon partially or fully inflated is the injury — not the intended action. This is the distractor designed to test whether students know that balloon deflation must happen first. *This is the most dangerous option presented and should be immediately recognized as contraindicated.*\n\n---",
