      "explanation": "**Rationales:**\n\n✅ **C — Correct.** Normal serum sodium is 136–145 mEq/L. A sodium level of 143 mEq/L falls within this normal range, indicating that the previously elevated sodium (>145 mEq/L) has been corrected. This is a direct laboratory indication of improvement in hypernatremia.\n\n❌ **A — Incorrect.** A blood pressure of 90/60 mmHg is hypotensive and indicates worsening clinical status — possible hypovolemia, hemodynamic instability, or shock. This does not represent improvement in any electrolyte disorder. *Hypotension would prompt immediate assessment and intervention — it is not a sign of electrolyte correction.*\n\n❌ **B — Incorrect.** Dry mucous membranes are a classic sign of hypernatremia and dehydration — they indicate that the condition has not improved. Improved hydration and normalizing sodium levels would be accompanied by moist mucous membranes. *Dry mucous membranes are a finding that indicates the problem persists, not that it is resolving.*\n\n❌ **D — Incorrect.** Increased thirst is the body's physiological response to elevated serum osmolality and is one of the presenting symptoms of hypernatremia. Persistent or worsening thirst indicates the condition has not been corrected. *Resolution of hypernatremia would be accompanied by decreased thirst.*\n\n---",
