      "explanation": "**Rationales:**\n\n✅ **C — Correct.** The gag reflex is a protective airway mechanism that prevents aspiration of foreign material. In an unconscious patient, the gag reflex may be absent or diminished. Before introducing any fluid, foam swab, or instrument into the mouth, the nurse must assess whether a gag reflex is present. If absent, the patient is at high risk for aspirating oral secretions or oral care solutions into the lungs, potentially causing aspiration pneumonia. Lateral positioning and suctioning availability are additional precautions, but gag reflex assessment is the priority before beginning.\n\n❌ **A — Incorrect.** Plaque buildup is an oral hygiene finding that the nurse may note during the oral care procedure itself, but it is not a safety assessment that determines whether the procedure can be safely initiated. *Plaque assessment occurs as part of the oral examination, not as a pre-procedure safety screen.*\n\n❌ **B — Incorrect.** Oral odor is a relevant clinical finding that may indicate infection, poor hygiene, or systemic disease, but it does not determine the safety of proceeding with oral care. It is an assessment finding, not a prerequisite safety check. *Oral odor might prompt more thorough oral care, but its presence or absence doesn't change the safety protocol.*\n\n❌ **D — Incorrect.** Frequency of oral care is a care planning consideration — oral care for unconscious patients should be performed every 2–4 hours to prevent hospital-acquired pneumonia — but it is not an assessment performed before initiating oral care. *Frequency is a care plan element established during planning, not an immediate pre-care assessment.*\n\n---",
