      "correctAnswerText": "A, C, D, E",
      "explanation": "**Rationales:**\n\n✅ **A — Correct.** Oxygen cylinders must be stored away from heat sources, open flames, and direct sunlight. Heat increases the internal pressure of compressed gas cylinders and significantly increases fire risk.\n\n❌ **B — Incorrect.** Petroleum jelly (Vaseline) is petroleum-based and therefore flammable — it combusts readily in an oxygen-enriched environment. It must never be used near supplemental oxygen. Water-soluble lubricants or specially formulated oxygen-compatible products should be used instead to moisten lips and nostrils. *This is one of the most commonly tested home oxygen safety violations.*\n\n✅ **C — Correct.** No-smoking signs alert everyone in and around the home that supplemental oxygen is in use and that smoking is prohibited. Oxygen dramatically accelerates combustion — a cigarette near an oxygen-enriched environment can trigger a devastating fire.\n\n✅ **D — Correct.** Ungrounded electrical equipment can generate sparks, which are ignition sources in an oxygen-enriched environment. All electrical devices used near oxygen must be properly grounded.\n\n✅ **E — Correct.** Oxygen cylinders must be stored and transported in the upright position and secured to prevent falling. If a cylinder falls and its valve is sheared off, the compressed gas can propel it with lethal force.\n\n---",
