      "correctAnswerText": "B",
      "explanation": "**Rationales:**\n\n✅ **B — Correct.** Two assessments are essential before applying heat: (1) **Sensation** — can the patient detect heat and temperature changes? If sensation is impaired (e.g., diabetic neuropathy, peripheral vascular disease, spinal cord injury), the patient cannot perceive a burn and will not withdraw from a damaging heat source. (2) **Circulation** — is blood flow adequate to the area? Impaired circulation means tissues cannot adequately dissipate heat, increasing the risk of thermal injury even at temperatures that would be safe for normally perfused tissue.\n\n❌ **A — Incorrect.** Skin turgor assesses hydration status — it is performed by gently pinching skin on the back of the hand or forehead and observing how quickly it returns to normal. While it is a useful general assessment, it does not inform the safety decision about applying heat. *Skin turgor assessment is relevant for fluid balance evaluation, not thermal application safety.*\n\n❌ **C — Incorrect.** Assessing pain level is appropriate before and after many interventions and is part of good nursing practice. However, in the specific context of applying a warm compress, the safety-critical assessments are sensation and circulation — not pain level. *Pain assessment would be performed as part of the overall evaluation, but it is not the priority pre-application safety check for heat application.*\n\n❌ **D — Incorrect.** The presence of edema may be relevant to note and could influence the clinical decision about applying heat (since heat can worsen edema in some acute inflammatory conditions), but it is not the primary safety assessment before a warm compress. *Edema assessment might cause the nurse to reconsider the intervention, but sensation and circulation are the direct safety determinants.*\n\n---",
