      "explanation": "**Rationales:**\n\n✅ **B — Correct.** Per TJC and CMS standards, physical restraints are a last resort and may only be applied after all reasonable alternatives have been attempted and found to be insufficient. Alternatives include: bed alarms, 1:1 sitters, reorientation and distraction, relocation closer to the nurses' station, removing IV lines or catheters if clinically feasible, and family visitation. Documenting that alternatives were tried and failed is required before applying restraints.\n\n❌ **A — Incorrect.** PRN (as needed) restraint orders for agitation are not permitted under TJC and CMS guidelines. Restraints cannot be ordered on a standing PRN basis — each episode of restraint use requires a specific, time-limited order based on a current clinical assessment. *PRN restraint orders represent a historical practice that has been eliminated from modern standards.*\n\n❌ **C — Incorrect.** Wandering alone is not a sufficient indication for restraints, particularly since restraints for wandering prevention carry significant risks (falls, entrapment, aspiration, psychological distress) that may outweigh the risk of wandering itself. Alternatives such as secured units, bed alarms, and sitters must be exhausted first. *Wandering in a cognitively impaired patient is managed through environmental and behavioral strategies, not routine restraint.*\n\n❌ **D — Incorrect.** A blanket vest restraint order for 48 hours is not an appropriate restraint order. Restraint orders are time-limited — typically a maximum of 24 hours for non-behavioral restraints — and must be renewed after reassessment. A 48-hour open-ended order violates restraint standards. *All restraint orders must be time-limited and require renewal after clinical reassessment.*\n\n---",
