      "explanation": "**Rationales:**\n\n✅ **D — Correct.** Grimacing and guarding are nonverbal pain indicators — behavioral expressions of pain that the patient may not be verbalizing due to stoicism, cognitive impairment, cultural norms, or belief that they shouldn't bother the nurse. These signs obligate the nurse to directly and explicitly ask the patient about pain. The patient's self-report is the most reliable pain assessment tool; nonverbal cues are the prompt to elicit it.\n\n❌ **A — Incorrect.** Offering food has no relevance to a patient showing signs of abdominal pain and guarding. Introducing food to a patient who may have an acute abdominal condition could be harmful, and it completely fails to address the clinical concern. *This option has no logical clinical basis in this scenario.*\n\n❌ **B — Incorrect.** Documenting signs of pain is a necessary step but it is not the first or most important action. Documentation captures what was observed, but it does not constitute assessment. The nurse must ask the patient directly before documenting the clinical picture. *Documentation follows assessment — observing behavioral cues and documenting them without asking the patient is an incomplete assessment.*\n\n❌ **C — Incorrect.** Asking specifically about constipation narrows the clinical inquiry to one possible cause before completing a thorough assessment. Abdominal guarding and grimacing can indicate many conditions — appendicitis, postoperative pain, ileus, bowel obstruction. Assuming constipation without a broader assessment risks missing a serious diagnosis. *This would be an appropriate specific question after a general open-ended pain assessment, not as the first question.*\n\n---",
