      "explanation": "**Rationales:**\n\n✅ **C — Correct.** Urinary retention — inability to void despite a full bladder — is a recognized complication after urinary catheter removal. The bladder may have become hypotonic from prolonged decompression, or bladder muscle function may be temporarily impaired. A full bladder with no void for 6–8 hours warrants bladder scanning and potentially recatheterization. The standard expectation is that the patient voids within 4–6 hours of catheter removal.\n\n❌ **A — Incorrect.** Voiding within 6 hours of catheter removal is the expected, normal outcome — not a complication. *This is what the nurse hopes to see after catheter removal.*\n\n❌ **B — Incorrect.** A urine output of 100 mL/hr is within the normal range (30–50 mL/hr minimum; 80–100 mL/hr is normal and reflects adequate hydration and renal function). This is not a complication. *Normal urine output does not indicate a problem.*\n\n❌ **D — Incorrect.** A mild burning sensation during the first few voids after catheter removal is a very common and expected finding — the result of urethral irritation from the catheter. It typically resolves quickly and does not require intervention. *Mild post-catheter dysuria is expected; severe or worsening dysuria with other signs would warrant assessment.*\n\n---",
