      "id": 79,
      "title": "Dry Flaky Skin: Best Intervention",
      "topic": "Hygiene & Skin Care",
      "concept": "Skin Care; Older Adults; Dry Skin",
      "unitId": 11,
      "questionText": "A bedridden client has dry, flaky skin. What is the best nursing intervention?",
      "options": [
        {
          "id": "A",
          "text": "Use alcohol-based cleansers"
        },
        {
          "id": "B",
          "text": "Apply talcum powder"
        },
        {
          "id": "C",
          "text": "Bathe with warm water and apply emollient"
        },
        {
          "id": "D",
          "text": "Wash skin every shift with soap"
        }
      ],
      "correctIds": [
        "C"
      ],
      "correctAnswerText": "C",
      "explanation": "**Rationales:**\n\n✅ **C — Correct.** Warm water (not hot — which further strips oils) cleanses the skin without harsh chemical disruption, while a follow-up emollient (moisturizer/lotion) replaces the lipid barrier that aging sebaceous glands can no longer produce adequately. This combination is the evidence-based standard for managing dry skin in older adults and bedridden patients.\n\n❌ **A — Incorrect.** Alcohol-based cleansers further dehydrate already-dry skin by dissolving the natural lipid barrier, worsening flaking and increasing the risk of skin breakdown. *Alcohol-based products are appropriate for hand sanitization but are specifically contraindicated for skin care in patients with dry or fragile skin.*\n\n❌ **B — Incorrect.** Talcum powder absorbs surface moisture initially but then clumps in skin folds, creating abrasive particles that irritate and damage fragile skin. It also carries health risks (inhalation concerns) and does not address the underlying dryness. *Talcum powder has no role in evidence-based skin care for dry or fragile skin.*\n\n❌ **D — Incorrect.** Washing with soap every shift removes the natural skin oils (sebum) that protect the skin barrier. Frequent soap exposure — especially in an older adult with already-decreased sebaceous activity — accelerates skin drying and fragility. *Bathing frequency for older adults or bedridden patients should be reduced and soap use minimized.*\n\n---",
