      "explanation": "**Rationales:**\n\n❌ **A — Incorrect:** This describes the opposite of correct log-rolling technique. Log-rolling requires the entire body to turn as a single, simultaneous unit. If one nurse turns the torso while another turns the legs independently, the spine is subjected to rotational and twisting forces — precisely the forces log-rolling is designed to prevent. Post-spinal surgery patients are vulnerable to hardware displacement, spinal instability, or cord injury from uncoordinated movement. The technique requires all nurses to move the patient in unison on a single coordinated count.\n\n✅ **B — Correct:** The defining principle of log-rolling is that the **head, shoulders, and hips maintain perfect spinal alignment** throughout the entire turn — the body moves as if it were a rigid log. This prevents axial rotation of the spine. At minimum two nurses (often three for larger patients) are needed: one supports the head and cervical spine, one supports the torso, and one supports the pelvis and legs. A single verbal count (\"1, 2, 3, turn\") ensures simultaneous coordinated movement.\n\n❌ **C — Incorrect:** A drawsheet is not contraindicated — it is a practical, recommended tool for log-rolling. Placing a drawsheet beneath the patient allows each nurse to grasp the sheet firmly, providing even distribution of force and better control during the turn. It reduces the risk of nurses losing grip and introduces no spinal risk when used correctly. *Note: The key requirement is alignment — a drawsheet assists this rather than compromising it.*\n\n❌ **D — Incorrect:** The legs must remain **straight and extended** during the rolling movement. Bending the hips causes pelvic rotation, which transmits rotational forces directly to the lumbar spine. Maintaining extended legs keeps the lumbar spine and pelvis in neutral alignment throughout the turn. A pillow may be placed between the knees once the patient reaches the side-lying position, but during the roll itself the legs stay straight.\n\n---",
