      "correctIds": [
        "C"
      ],
      "correctAnswerText": "C",
      "explanation": "**Rationales:**\n\n❌ **A — Incorrect:** \"Tolerated well\" is vague, subjective language that provides no clinical data. It does not specify equipment used, number of passes, secretion characteristics, or objective patient response. Legally and professionally, this does not meet documentation standards. If the patient's condition later changes, this entry provides no baseline for comparison.\n\n❌ **B — Incorrect:** \"No complications\" is an unsubstantiated interpretation — it does not document the objective findings that would support or refute the assertion. What was the SpO₂? What secretions were obtained? How many passes were performed? Without this data, \"no complications\" cannot be verified. This entry fails to provide the clinical detail required for safe continuity of care.\n\n✅ **C — Correct:** This entry meets all documentation standards — it is specific, objective, and outcome-oriented:\n- **Catheter size** (12 Fr) — documents the equipment used and the appropriateness for the patient's airway\n- **Number of passes** (×2) — documents procedure intensity and allows monitoring of trends\n- **Secretion character** (thick yellow) — provides clinically significant infection surveillance data; color, consistency, and amount are all relevant\n- **Patient response** (SpO₂ remained >95%) — documents that the patient tolerated the procedure without clinically significant desaturation\n\nThis level of detail allows the next nurse to assess for changes, identify trends, and evaluate whether the procedure achieved its intended purpose.\n\n❌ **D — Incorrect:** \"Secretions noted; suctioned with catheter\" is the most minimal and clinically useless entry of the options. It documents only that something happened — it provides no data about type of catheter, number of passes, secretion characteristics, or patient response. This entry could not support any clinical decision-making, legal defense, or quality review.\n\n---",
