      "explanation": "**Rationales:**\n\n❌ **A — Incorrect:** Clear breath sounds after suctioning indicate that secretions have been successfully removed from the airway — this is the **desired outcome** of the procedure. No further action is required based on this finding; it should be documented as a positive response to suctioning.\n\n✅ **B — Correct:** A drop in SpO₂ from 96% to 88% represents an **8-percentage-point desaturation** — a clinically significant decline requiring immediate intervention. Post-suctioning hypoxemia occurs when suctioning removes too much oxygen from the airway. At 88%, the patient is outside normal range and showing significant respiratory compromise. The nurse must: stop suctioning, apply supplemental oxygen, allow recovery time, and reassess before considering additional passes. If SpO₂ does not recover, the provider must be notified.\n\n❌ **C — Incorrect:** A slight increase in heart rate during or immediately after suctioning is an **expected physiological response** — the sympathetic nervous system activates in response to the mild discomfort of suctioning, the vagal stimulation from catheter contact with the airway, and any brief hypoxemia. A modest, transient HR increase that resolves quickly is normal. This finding requires monitoring but not immediate intervention.\n\n❌ **D — Incorrect:** Coughing during suctioning is an **expected and therapeutically desirable response** — it indicates an intact cough reflex and actually helps mobilize secretions upward toward the catheter tip. Coughing during suctioning is not a complication; it is a normal protective airway reflex demonstrating intact neurological function.\n\n---",
